TikTok hides unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
Imagine China / Reuters
China’s TikTok social network censors videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibet’s independence, or the banned religious group Falun Gong.
The documents found in the publication tell that the owner of TikTok (ByteDance company) with the help of the application promotes the goals of China's foreign policy abroad.
Most of the violations related to China’s policy fall under the “hate incitement”.
In each case, TikTok places undesirable publications in a context appropriate to the general rules so that the actions of the social network do not look censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of China’s socialist system falls under the general ban on “criticizing or attacking the politics and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc.”.
The ban on mentioning the Tiananmen Square incidents or the genocide in Cambodia falls under the "distortion of the history of China or other countries".
The document also lists the banned names of twenty "foreign leaders or statesmen", including North Korean leaders Kim Jong Il, Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, U.S. Presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Jozo Abe, and South Korean President Park Kyo.
Prohibited material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Posts from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may result in the blocking of the user.
Not too strict violations belong to the second category: such publications remain on the site, but their distribution is limited to TikTok algorithms.
ByteDance told The Guardian that these rules are outdated and no longer applicable: “We are now using a localized approach for moderation, as well as engaging independent local specialists.”
Russian users of TikTok have no specific restrictions on publications, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the "Producer Center".
"Producer Center" is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Producer Center" agrees with the representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without agreement, Bogdanov reports.
When asked if TikTok can comment on politics or Putin, Bogdanov responds in the affirmative and says that he has seen such publications.
Bogdanov agrees with the founder of the agency Our Didgital Roman Zaripov: "The basic rules for users TikTok lists in the user agreement: you should not post shocking content, discriminatory statements and so on."
But under these rules, you can bring any content that does not like moderators, notes Zaripov.
Zaripov Agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users in the world exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under the age of 18.
According to the user agreement, TikTok can only be used by persons over 13 years of age.
The administrators of the social network check their age with the help of artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, says Bogdanov.
If the neural network decides that the user is younger, his account may be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of the coworking WeWork.
